niversity Teleilat Ghassul Project 1; BAR International Series 974). Oxford: British Archaeological Reports.\n*{{Citation|title= [[History of Syria: including Lebanon and Palestine|History of Syria including Lebanon and Palestine]] |first= Philip Khuri |last=Hitti |publisher= Gorgias Press LLC |year= 2004 |isbn= 978-1-59333-119-1  }}\n*History of the Land - Israel, Volume I, edited by Joel Rappel, 1980, {{ISBN|978-9650500504}}. Pp 47-60 in the Hebrew 1980 edition: The Land Of Israel in the Chalcolithic Era, by [[David Ussishkin]]. \n\n== External links ==\n*  Paul James Cowie, Archaeowiki: [http://www.archaeowiki.org/Teleilat_Ghassul Teleilat Ghassul]\n*  Andie Byrnes, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070218000617/http://www.near-east.historians.co.uk/html/chalcolithic.html The Chalcolithic]\n*  Paul James Cowie, Archaeowiki: [http://www.archaeowiki.org/Chalcolithic_of_the_Southern_Levant Chalcolithic of the Southern Levant]\n\n{{coord|31|51|39|N|35|38|26|E|type:landmark_source:kolossus-hewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological cultures of West Asia]]\n[[Category:Chalcolithic cultures of Asia]]\n\n[[Category:Archaeological cultures in Israel]]\n[[Category:Archaeological cultures in Jordan]]\n[[Category:Archaeological cultures in Palestine]]\n[[Category:Ancient Levant]]\n", "name_user": "Sumanuil", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghassulian"}
{"title_page": "Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Nadal|Homar}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal\n| image = Miguel Angel Nadal in 2016.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Nadal in 2016\n| fullname = Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal Homar\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|7|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manacor]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.88}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] / [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1980\u20131983 | youthclubs1 = [[CD Manacor|Manacor]]\n| years1 = 1983\u20131986 | clubs1 = [[CD Manacor|Manacor]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps2 = 20 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 1987\u20131991 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 130 | goals3 = 22\n| years4 = 1991\u20131999 | clubs4 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps4 = 208 | goals4 = 12\n| years5 = 1999\u20132005 | clubs5 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps5 = 149 | goals5 = 6\n| totalcaps = 507 | totalgoals = 41\n| nationalyears1 = 1991\u20132002 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps1 = 62 | nationalgoals1= 3\n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132011 | managerclubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2011 | managerclubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (caretaker)\n}}\n{{IPA notice}}\n'''Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal Homar''' ({{IPA-es|mi\u02c8\u0263el \u02c8a\u014bxel na\u02c8\u00f0al o\u02c8ma\u027e}}, {{lang-ca|Miquel \u00c0ngel Nadal Homar}}; born 28 July 1966) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]]. Nicknamed ''The Beast'',<ref name=BEAST>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/11/europeanfootball.sport|title=The beauty of the beast|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 September 2001|accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> he based his game in a tremendous physical display, also being adaptable to various [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and [[midfielder]] positions.\n\nHe began and ended his career with [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]], but his greatest achievements came whilst at [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] during the so-called ''[[FC Barcelona#Dream Team|Dream Team]]'' era. Over 19 professional seasons, he played 492 matches (462 of those in [[La Liga]]).\n\nA very important part of [[Spain national football team|Spain]]'s setup during the 1990s, Nadal represented the nation in three [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] and at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]]. In 2007, ''[[The Times]]'' placed him at number 47 in their list of the 50 hardest footballers in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/forum/printable.asp?m=1554851|title=Top 50 hardest footballers|publisher=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=13 August 2007|accessdate=23 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019002225/http://www.empireonline.com/forum/printable.asp?m=1554851|archivedate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Manacor]], [[Majorca]], [[Balearic Islands]], Nadal made his debut in [[La Liga]] with local [[RCD Mallorca]], first appearing on 19 April 1987 against [[FC Barcelona]] at the [[Camp Nou]]. In his final two seasons, after helping in a [[1988\u201389 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1989 promotion]] from [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], he scored 12 goals from 72 league appearances, thus being acquired by the [[Catalonia]] club for the [[1991\u201392 La Liga|1991\u201392 campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdm.es/jugadores-de-ayer-y-de-hoy-miguel-angel-nadal/|title=Jugadores de ayer y de hoy: Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal|trans-title=Players from tomorrow and today: Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal|publisher=RCDM|last=Busquets|first=Dami\u00e0|language=Spanish|date=18 February 2009|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith ''Bar\u00e7a'', under [[Johan Cruyff]], Nadal was a very important part in the conquest of five leagues, two [[Copa del Rey]] and the [[1991\u201392 European Cup|1992 European Cup]], playing in over 300 overall games and occupying several defensive positions in both the back-four and in midfield. In his last year, however, ostracised by another Dutch coach, [[Louis van Gaal]], he only appeared in two matches; in 1996 and 1997 he was linked with a transfer to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], but the move to the [[Premier League]] never materialised.<ref name=BEAST/>\n\nSubsequently Nadal returned to Mallorca, starting strong and only missing 11 contests in his first three seasons combined, while also being important in the [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|2003 domestic cup conquest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/06/29/deportes/1056837603_850215.html|title=Eto'o pone Mallorca a brindar|trans-title=Eto'o has Mallorca toasting|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Miguelez|first=Jos\u00e9|language=Spanish|date=29 June 2003|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> He retired from the game at almost 39, having appeared in nearly 700 official matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cadenaser.com/deportes/articulo/miguel-angel-nadal-anuncio-viernes-retirada/csrcsrpor/20050304csrcsrdep_8/Tes|title=Miguel Angel Nadal anunci\u00f3 este viernes su retirada|trans-title=Miguel Angel Nadal announced retirement this Friday|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|language=Spanish|date=4 March 2005|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, five years after his retirement, Nadal returned to Mallorca, joining the coaching staff under [[Michael Laudrup]], his Barcelona teammate during three seasons. As the [[Denmark|Dane]] left the club in late September 2011 following a run-in with director [[Lorenzo Serra Ferrer]], Nadal was in charge for one game, a 2\u20132 away draw against [[CA Osasuna]], but he too left the following week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/10/10/futbol/equipos/mallorca/1318240186.html|title=Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal hace oficial su marcha del Mallorca|trans-title=Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal makes departure from Mallorca official|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=10 October 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nNadal earned 62 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]], his debut coming on 13 November 1991 in a [[UEFA Euro 1992]] [[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying|qualifier]] dead rubber against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] (the national team had virtually no chances of reaching the finals in [[Sweden]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1991/11/14/pagina-3/1243555/pdf.html|title=Espa\u00f1a, de penalty y regalado|trans-title=Spain, from a gifted penalty|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Rogelio|language=Spanish|date=14 November 1991|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> He went on to appear with the country in three [[FIFA World Cup]]s.\n\nAdditionally, Nadal missed a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] against [[England national football team|England]], in a [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]] [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|shootout]] loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=223/match=52911/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Hosts England first team into last four|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> After appearing in four complete matches at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], at almost 36, he retired from the international scene.<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/nadal-intl.html|title=Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal Homar \u2013 International Matches|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|last=Pla Diaz|first=Emilio|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n<ref name=RSSSF/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 16 November 1994 || [[Ram\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Pizju\u00e1n Stadium|S\u00e1nchez Pizju\u00e1n]], [[Seville]], Spain || {{fb|DEN}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 3\u20130 || [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying Group 2|Euro 1996 qualifying]]\n|-\n| 2. || 30 November 1994 || [[Estadio La Rosaleda|La Rosaleda]], [[M\u00e1laga]], Spain || {{fb|FIN}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 2\u20130 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 3. || 5 September 2001 || [[Rheinpark Stadion|Rheinpark]], [[Vaduz]], [[Liechtenstein]] || {{fb|LIE}} || 0\u2013'''2''' || 0\u20132 || [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 7|2002 World Cup qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nNadal is the paternal uncle of professional [[tennis]] player [[Rafael Nadal]], whilst his brother [[Toni Nadal|Toni]] was Rafael's coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2005/07/17/deportes/1121551213_850215.html|title=Rafa Nadal tambi\u00e9n golea|trans-title=Rafa Nadal also scores|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|last=Men\u00e9ndez|first=Manu|language=Spanish|date=17 July 2005|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diariosur.es/agencias/20110913/deportes/mas-deportes/miquel-angel-nadal-dice-derrota_201109131933.html|title=Miquel \u00c1ngel Nadal dice que la derrota \"ha dignificado a Rafa\"|trans-title=Miquel \u00c1ngel Nadal says defeat \"has dignified Rafa\"|newspaper=[[Diario Sur]]|language=Spanish|date=13 September 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/summer08/fanguide/athlete?athlete=72811|title=Rafael Nadal|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Barcelona'''\n*[[La Liga]]: [[1991\u201392 La Liga|1991\u201392]], [[1992\u201393 La Liga|1992\u201393]], [[1993\u201394 La Liga|1993\u201394]], [[1997\u201398 La Liga|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[1996\u201397 Copa del Rey|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Copa del Rey|1997\u201398]]\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[1991 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1991]], [[1992 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1992]], [[1994 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1994]], [[1996 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1996]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]: [[1991\u201392 European Cup|1991\u201392]]\n*[[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]: [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|1996\u201397]]\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[1992 European Super Cup|1992]], [[1997 UEFA Super Cup|1997]]\n\n'''Mallorca'''\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|2002\u201303]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BDFutbol|2045}}\n* {{NFT player|id=14108}}\n* {{FIFA player|77908}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Spain squads\n|bg = #db000d\n|fg = #fbea0e\n|list1 =\n{{Spain squad 1994 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Spain squad UEFA Euro 1996}}\n{{Spain squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Spain squad 2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{RCD Mallorca managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nadal, Miguel Angel}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Manacor]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Balearic footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Nadal|Homar}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal\n| image = Miguel Angel Nadal in 2016.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Nadal in 2016\n| fullname = Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal Homar\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|7|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manacor]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.88}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] / [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1980\u20131983 | youthclubs1 = [[CD Manacor|Manacor]]\n| years1 = 1983\u20131986 | clubs1 = [[CD Manacor|Manacor]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps2 = 20 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 1987\u20131991 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 130 | goals3 = 22\n| years4 = 1991\u20131999 | clubs4 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps4 = 208 | goals4 = 12\n| years5 = 1999\u20132005 | clubs5 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps5 = 149 | goals5 = 6\n| totalcaps = 507 | totalgoals = 41\n| nationalyears1 = 1991\u20132002 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps1 = 62 | nationalgoals1= 3\n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132011 | managerclubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2011 | managerclubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (caretaker)\n}}\n{{IPA notice}}\n'''Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal Homar''' ({{IPA-es|mi\u02c8\u0263el \u02c8a\u014bxel na\u02c8\u00f0al o\u02c8ma\u027e}}, {{lang-ca|Miquel \u00c0ngel Nadal Homar}}; born 28 July 1966) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]]. Nicknamed ''The Beast'',<ref name=BEAST>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/11/europeanfootball.sport|title=The beauty of the beast|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 September 2001|accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> he based his game in a tremendous physical display, also being adaptable to various [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and [[midfielder]] positions.\n\nHe began and ended his career with [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]], but his greatest achievements came whilst at [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] during the so-called ''[[FC Barcelona#Dream Team|Dream Team]]'' era. Over 19 professional seasons, he played 492 matches (462 of those in [[La Liga]]).\n\nA very important part of [[Spain national football team|Spain]]'s setup during the 1990s, Nadal represented the nation in three [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] and at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]]. In 2007, ''[[The Times]]'' placed him at number 47 in their list of the 50 hardest footballers in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/forum/printable.asp?m=1554851|title=Top 50 hardest footballers|publisher=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=13 August 2007|accessdate=23 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019002225/http://www.empireonline.com/forum/printable.asp?m=1554851|archivedate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Manacor]], [[Majorca]], [[Balearic Islands]], Nadal made his debut in [[La Liga]] with local [[RCD Mallorca]], first appearing on 19 April 1987 against [[FC Barcelona]] at the [[Camp Nou]]. In his final two seasons, after helping in a [[1988\u201389 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1989 promotion]] from [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], he scored 12 goals from 72 league appearances, thus being acquired by the [[Catalonia]] club for the [[1991\u201392 La Liga|1991\u201392 campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdm.es/jugadores-de-ayer-y-de-hoy-miguel-angel-nadal/|title=Jugadores de ayer y de hoy: Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal|trans-title=Players from tomorrow and today: Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal|publisher=RCDM|last=Busquets|first=Dami\u00e0|language=Spanish|date=18 February 2009|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith ''Bar\u00e7a'', under [[Johan Cruyff]], Nadal was a very important part in the conquest of five leagues, two [[Copa del Rey]] and the [[1991\u201392 European Cup|1992 European Cup]], playing in over 300 overall games and occupying several defensive positions in both the back-four and in midfield. In his last year, however, ostracised by another Dutch coach, [[Louis van Gaal]], he only appeared in two matches; in 1996 and 1997 he was linked with a transfer to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], but the move to the [[Premier League]] never materialised.<ref name=BEAST/>\n\nSubsequently Nadal returned to Mallorca, starting strong and only missing 11 contests in his first three seasons combined, while also being important in the [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|2003 domestic cup conquest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/06/29/deportes/1056837603_850215.html|title=Eto'o pone Mallorca a brindar|trans-title=Eto'o has Mallorca toasting|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Miguelez|first=Jos\u00e9|language=Spanish|date=29 June 2003|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> He retired from the game at almost 39, having appeared in nearly 700 official matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cadenaser.com/deportes/articulo/miguel-angel-nadal-anuncio-viernes-retirada/csrcsrpor/20050304csrcsrdep_8/Tes|title=Miguel Angel Nadal anunci\u00f3 este viernes su retirada|trans-title=Miguel Angel Nadal announced retirement this Friday|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|language=Spanish|date=4 March 2005|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, five years after his retirement, Nadal returned to Mallorca, joining the coaching staff under [[Michael Laudrup]], his Barcelona teammate during three seasons. As the [[Denmark|Dane]] left the club in late September 2011 following a run-in with director [[Lorenzo Serra Ferrer]], Nadal was in charge for one game, a 2\u20132 away draw against [[CA Osasuna]], but he too left the following week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/10/10/futbol/equipos/mallorca/1318240186.html|title=Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal hace oficial su marcha del Mallorca|trans-title=Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal makes departure from Mallorca official|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=10 October 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nNadal earned 62 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]], his debut coming on 13 November 1991 in a [[UEFA Euro 1992]] [[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying|qualifier]] dead rubber against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] (the national team had virtually no chances of reaching the finals in [[Sweden]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1991/11/14/pagina-3/1243555/pdf.html|title=Espa\u00f1a, de penalty y regalado|trans-title=Spain, from a gifted penalty|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Rogelio|language=Spanish|date=14 November 1991|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> He went on to appear with the country in three [[FIFA World Cup]]s.\n\nAdditionally, Nadal missed a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] against [[England national football team|England]], in a [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]] [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|shootout]] loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=223/match=52911/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Hosts England first team into last four|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> After appearing in four complete matches at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], at almost 36, he retired from the international scene.<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/nadal-intl.html|title=Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal Homar \u2013 International Matches|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|last=Pla Diaz|first=Emilio|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n<ref name=RSSSF/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 16 November 1994 || [[Ram\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Pizju\u00e1n Stadium|S\u00e1nchez Pizju\u00e1n]], [[Seville]], Spain || {{fb|DEN}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 3\u20130 || [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying Group 2|Euro 1996 qualifying]]\n|-\n| 2. || 30 November 1994 || [[Estadio La Rosaleda|La Rosaleda]], [[M\u00e1laga]], Spain || {{fb|FIN}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 2\u20130 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 3. || 5 September 2001 || [[Rheinpark Stadion|Rheinpark]], [[Vaduz]], [[Liechtenstein]] || {{fb|LIE}} || 0\u2013'''2''' || 0\u20132 || [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 7|2002 World Cup qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nNadal was the paternal uncle of professional [[tennis]] player [[Rafael Nadal]], whilst his brother [[Toni Nadal|Toni]] was Rafael's coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2005/07/17/deportes/1121551213_850215.html|title=Rafa Nadal tambi\u00e9n golea|trans-title=Rafa Nadal also scores|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|last=Men\u00e9ndez|first=Manu|language=Spanish|date=17 July 2005|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diariosur.es/agencias/20110913/deportes/mas-deportes/miquel-angel-nadal-dice-derrota_201109131933.html|title=Miquel \u00c1ngel Nadal dice que la derrota \"ha dignificado a Rafa\"|trans-title=Miquel \u00c1ngel Nadal says defeat \"has dignified Rafa\"|newspaper=[[Diario Sur]]|language=Spanish|date=13 September 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/summer08/fanguide/athlete?athlete=72811|title=Rafael Nadal|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Barcelona'''\n*[[La Liga]]: [[1991\u201392 La Liga|1991\u201392]], [[1992\u201393 La Liga|1992\u201393]], [[1993\u201394 La Liga|1993\u201394]], [[1997\u201398 La Liga|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[1996\u201397 Copa del Rey|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Copa del Rey|1997\u201398]]\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[1991 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1991]], [[1992 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1992]], [[1994 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1994]], [[1996 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1996]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]: [[1991\u201392 European Cup|1991\u201392]]\n*[[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]: [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|1996\u201397]]\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[1992 European Super Cup|1992]], [[1997 UEFA Super Cup|1997]]\n\n'''Mallorca'''\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|2002\u201303]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BDFutbol|2045}}\n* {{NFT player|id=14108}}\n* {{FIFA player|77908}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Spain squads\n|bg = #db000d\n|fg = #fbea0e\n|list1 =\n{{Spain squad 1994 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Spain squad UEFA Euro 1996}}\n{{Spain squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Spain squad 2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{RCD Mallorca managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nadal, Miguel Angel}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Manacor]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Balearic footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca managers]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:6093:ed00:1d94:6439:850d:7d00", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Changing first sentence to a present tense.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miguel_%C3%81ngel_Nadal"}
{"title_page": "Anti Social Social Club", "text_new": "{{Infobox brand\n| name           = Anti Social Social Club\n| logo           = Anti Social Social Club logo.svg\n| logo_upright   = \n| logo_alt       = \n| logo_caption   = \n| image          = \n| image_upright  = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| producttype    = [[Clothing]] [[Streetwear]]\n| currentowner   = Neek Lurk\n\n| producedby     = \n| country        = {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Los Angeles]], [[United States]]\n| introduced     ={{start date and age|2015}} \n| discontinued   = \n| related        = \n| markets        = Worldwide\n| previousowners = \n| trademarkregistrations = \n| ambassadors    = \n| tagline        =Self Doubt \n| website        = {{URL|http://antisocialsocialclub.com}}\n| module         = <!-- or: misc -->\n| module1        = <!-- or: misc1 -->\n}}\n'''Anti Social Social Club''' (sometimes stylized as '''ASSC''' and '''AntiSocialSocialClub''') is a [[streetwear]] [[brand]] founded by Neek Lurk<ref>[https://hypebeast.com/2015/12/neek-lurk-anti-social-social-club-interview Neek Lurk: Manic Depressive, Sadistic, Masochist: A one-on-one exclusive interview with the eccentric founder of Anti Social Social Club.] Madrell Stinney, December, 7, 2015 </ref><ref>[https://amuse-i-d.vice.com/how-neek-lurk-made-money-from-melancholia/ How Neek Lurk Made Dem coins from Melancholia: The Anti Social Social Club founder on building fortmite hype through negativity] TIERNEY FINSTER, [[Vice Media]], March 30, 2016  </ref>, who previously worked for [[St\u00fcssy]] as a social marketing manager.<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/2016/08/09/neek-lurkinterview/ Neek Lurk Talks Founding Anti Social Social Club in New Interview]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Jake Boyer, [[Highsnobiety]], August 9, 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/12/neek-lurk-anti-social-social-club-interview|title=Neek Lurk: Manic Depressive, Sadistic, Masochist|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nThe brand has collaborated with [[A Bathing Ape]]<ref>[https://us.bape.com/blogs/news/a-bathing-ape-x-anti-social-social-club A BATHING APE\u00ae X ANTI SOCIAL SOCIAL CLUB] bape.com</ref>, [[Rimowa]]<ref>[.soul4street.com] soul4street.com</ref>, [[Dover Street Market]]<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/2017/10/04/new-anti-social-social-club-x-dover-street-market-capsule-dropping-friday/ A New Anti Social Social Club x Dover Street Market Capsule Is Dropping This Friday] Graeme Campbell, [[Highsnobiety]], October 4, 2017</ref>, [[Playboy Enterprises|Playboy]]<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/2017/09/18/playboy-anti-social-social-club-capsule/ Anti Social Social Club Taps \u2018Playboy\u2019 for Exclusive Capsule] Renz Ofiaza, [[Highsnobiety]], September 18, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.flaunt.com/content/fashion/anti-social-social-club-playboy-capsule ANTI SOCIAL SOCIAL CLUB & PLAYBOY ARE RELEASING A CAPSULE] Corey Fuller, ''[[Flaunt]]'' September 19, 2017</ref>, [[Hello Kitty]]<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/anti-social-social-club-fw18/ Anti Social Social Club's FW18 Drop Includes a Hello Kitty Collab] [[Highsnobiety]], August 18, 2018</ref> and [[Hotwheels]]<ref>[https://hypebeast.com/2019/11/anti-social-social-club-hot-wheels-collaboration-teaser/ ASSC x HOTWHEELS Drop of November 23. 2019]</ref>.\n\n==History==\n\nAnti Social Social Club was founded in 2015 through [[Instagram]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/antisocialsocialclub/|title=Anti Social Social Club \u00ae (@antisocialsocialclub) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and known as ASSC.\u00a0 Neek Lurk runs ASSC retail entirely online'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dhl-and-anti-social-social-club-launch-exclusive-collaboration-300923381.html|title=DHL and Anti Social Social Club Launch Exclusive Collaboration|last=DHL|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>''' without any physical store. It comes with limited collections each year. The inspiration for creating this brand came from his [[mental health]] struggle<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amuse.vice.com/en_us/article/438x7n/neek-lurk-money|title=Anti Social Social Club {{!}} How Neek Lurk Made Money from Melancholia|last=Finster|first=Tierney|date=2016-03-30|website=Amuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> at age 27. Neek used his brand as an emotional outlet for his depression. The first product was a basic hat with the logo on the side<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amuse.vice.com/en_us/article/438x7n/neek-lurk-money|title=Anti Social Social Club {{!}} How Neek Lurk Made Money from Melancholia|last=Finster|first=Tierney|date=2016-03-30|website=Amuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>. Shortly after its founding, ASSC became a popular trend. Some celebrities have worn this brand, like [[Kanye West]], [[BTS]], and [[Kim Kardashian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amuse.vice.com/en_us/article/qvyje5/anti-social-social-club-famous-fans|title=Anti Social Social Club {{!}} Kanye West, BTS, Kim Kardashian, and Other Famous Fans|last=Team|first=Amuse|date=2020-01-13|website=Amuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[A Bathing Ape]]\n*[[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Billionaire Boys Club]]\n*[[Virgil Abloh]]\n*[[OVO_Sound#OVO_Clothing|OVO]]\n*[[Chrome Hearts]]\n*[[The Hundreds]]\n*[[Freshjive]]\n*[[St\u00fcssy]]\n*[[Highsnobiety]]\n*[[Visvim]]\n*[[Rimowa]]\n*[[Hotwheels]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|http://antisocialsocialclub.com}}\n\n{{fashion-stub}}\n{{LosAngeles-stub}}\n\n[[Category:2010s fashion]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of the United States]]\n[[Category:Culture of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Hip hop fashion]]\n[[Category:Street fashion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox brand\n| name           = Anti Social Social Club\n| logo           = Anti Social Social Club logo.svg\n| logo_upright   = \n| logo_alt       = \n| logo_caption   = \n| image          = \n| image_upright  = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| producttype    = [[Clothing]] [[Streetwear]]\n| currentowner   = Neek Lurk\n\n| producedby     = \n| country        = {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Los Angeles]], [[United States]]\n| introduced     ={{start date and age|2015}} \n| discontinued   = \n| related        = \n| markets        = Worldwide\n| previousowners = \n| trademarkregistrations = \n| ambassadors    = \n| tagline        =Self Doubt \n| website        = {{URL|http://antisocialsocialclub.com}}\n| module         = <!-- or: misc -->\n| module1        = <!-- or: misc1 -->\n}}\n'''Anti Social Social Club''' (sometimes stylized as '''ASSC''' and '''AntiSocialSocialClub''') is a [[streetwear]] [[brand]] founded by Neek Lurk<ref>[https://hypebeast.com/2015/12/neek-lurk-anti-social-social-club-interview Neek Lurk: Manic Depressive, Sadistic, Masochist: A one-on-one exclusive interview with the eccentric founder of Anti Social Social Club.] Madrell Stinney, December, 7, 2015 </ref><ref>[https://amuse-i-d.vice.com/how-neek-lurk-made-money-from-melancholia/ How Neek Lurk Made Dem coins from Melancholia: The Anti Social Social Club founder on building fortmite hype through negativity] TIERNEY FINSTER, [[Vice Media]], March 30, 2016  </ref>, who previously worked for [[St\u00fcssy]] as a social marketing manager.<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/2016/08/09/neek-lurkinterview/ Neek Lurk Talks Founding Anti Social Social Club in New Interview]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Jake Boyer, [[Highsnobiety]], August 9, 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/12/neek-lurk-anti-social-social-club-interview|title=Neek Lurk: Manic Depressive, Sadistic, Masochist|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nThe brand has collaborated with [[A Bathing Ape]]<ref>[https://us.bape.com/blogs/news/a-bathing-ape-x-anti-social-social-club A BATHING APE\u00ae X ANTI SOCIAL SOCIAL CLUB] bape.com</ref>, [[Rimowa]]<ref>[.soul4street.com] soul4street.com</ref>, [[Dover Street Market]]<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/2017/10/04/new-anti-social-social-club-x-dover-street-market-capsule-dropping-friday/ A New Anti Social Social Club x Dover Street Market Capsule Is Dropping This Friday] Graeme Campbell, [[Highsnobiety]], October 4, 2017</ref>, [[Playboy Enterprises|Playboy]]<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/2017/09/18/playboy-anti-social-social-club-capsule/ Anti Social Social Club Taps \u2018Playboy\u2019 for Exclusive Capsule] Renz Ofiaza, [[Highsnobiety]], September 18, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.flaunt.com/content/fashion/anti-social-social-club-playboy-capsule ANTI SOCIAL SOCIAL CLUB & PLAYBOY ARE RELEASING A CAPSULE] Corey Fuller, ''[[Flaunt]]'' September 19, 2017</ref>, [[Hello Kitty]]<ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/anti-social-social-club-fw18/ Anti Social Social Club's FW18 Drop Includes a Hello Kitty Collab] [[Highsnobiety]], August 18, 2018</ref> and [[Hotwheels]]<ref>[https://hypebeast.com/2019/11/anti-social-social-club-hot-wheels-collaboration-teaser/ ASSC x HOTWHEELS Drop of November 23. 2019]</ref>.\n\n==History==\n\n'''Anti Social Social Club''' was founded in 2015 through [[Instagram]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/antisocialsocialclub/|title=Anti Social Social Club \u00ae (@antisocialsocialclub) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and known as ASSC.\u00a0 Neek Lurk runs ASSC retail entirely online'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dhl-and-anti-social-social-club-launch-exclusive-collaboration-300923381.html|title=DHL and Anti Social Social Club Launch Exclusive Collaboration|last=DHL|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>''' without any physical store. It comes with limited collections each year. The inspiration for creating this brand came from his [[mental health]] struggle<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amuse.vice.com/en_us/article/438x7n/neek-lurk-money|title=Anti Social Social Club {{!}} How Neek Lurk Made Money from Melancholia|last=Finster|first=Tierney|date=2016-03-30|website=Amuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> at age 27. Neek used his brand as an emotional outlet for his depression. The first product was a basic hat with the logo on the side<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amuse.vice.com/en_us/article/438x7n/neek-lurk-money|title=Anti Social Social Club {{!}} How Neek Lurk Made Money from Melancholia|last=Finster|first=Tierney|date=2016-03-30|website=Amuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>. Shortly after its founding, ASSC became a popular trend. Some celebrities have worn this brand, like [[Kanye West]], [[BTS]], and [[Kim Kardashian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amuse.vice.com/en_us/article/qvyje5/anti-social-social-club-famous-fans|title=Anti Social Social Club {{!}} Kanye West, BTS, Kim Kardashian, and Other Famous Fans|last=Team|first=Amuse|date=2020-01-13|website=Amuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[A Bathing Ape]]\n*[[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Billionaire Boys Club]]\n*[[Virgil Abloh]]\n*[[OVO_Sound#OVO_Clothing|OVO]]\n*[[Chrome Hearts]]\n*[[The Hundreds]]\n*[[Freshjive]]\n*[[St\u00fcssy]]\n*[[Highsnobiety]]\n*[[Visvim]]\n*[[Rimowa]]\n*[[Hotwheels]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|http://antisocialsocialclub.com}}\n\n{{fashion-stub}}\n{{LosAngeles-stub}}\n\n[[Category:2010s fashion]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of the United States]]\n[[Category:Culture of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Hip hop fashion]]\n[[Category:Street fashion]]\n", "name_user": "PorcSharpQuills", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:removing bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org