{"title_page": "Voyager of the Seas", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n | Ship image = Voyager of the Seas in Sydney.jpg\n | Ship caption = ''Voyager of the Seas'' in [[Sydney]], Australia,<br>following her 2014 refurbishment\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n | Hide header           =\n | Ship name             = ''Voyager of the Seas''\n | Ship owner            =  \n | Ship operator         = [[Royal Caribbean International]]\n | Ship registry         = * 1999\u20132002: {{flagicon|Liberia}} [[Monrovia]], Liberia\n* 2002\u2013present: {{flagicon|Bahamas}} [[Nassau, Bahamas]] \n | Ship route = Asia, Australia and New Zealand\n | Ship ordered =\n | Ship builder          = [[Kv\u00e6rner Masa-Yards]], [[Perno shipyard|Turku New Shipyard]], [[Turku]], Finland\n | Ship original cost    = {{US$|650 million}}\n | Ship yard number      = 1344\n | Ship way number =\n | Ship floated out =\n | Ship laid down = March 31, 1998\n | Ship launched         = November 27, 1998\n | Ship sponsor          = [[Katarina Witt]]\n | Ship completed = October 29, 1999\n | Ship christened       = November 20, 1999\n | Ship acquired         =\n | Ship maiden voyage    = November 21, 1999\n | Ship in service       =\n | Ship out of service   =\n | Ship identification   =* [[American Bureau of Shipping|ABS class no:]]\n* [[Call sign]]: C6SE5\n* {{ship register|DNV|19902}}\n* {{IMO Number|9161716}}\n* {{MMSI|311317000}}\n\n | Ship fate             =\n | Ship status           = In service\n | Ship notes            =  <ref name=\"dnv\">{{cite ship register |register=DNV |id=19902 |shipname=Voyager of the Seas |accessdate=18 June 2010 }}</ref>{{sfn|Smith|2010|p=166}}\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n | Ship class            = {{sclass-|Voyager|cruise ship}}\n | Ship length           = {{convert|311.1|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n | Ship beam             =* {{convert|38.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}} - Waterline\n* {{convert|47.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}} - Max<ref name=dnv/>\n | Ship height           = {{convert|63|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n | Ship draught          = {{convert|9.1|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n | Ship tonnage          =*{{GT|138,194}}\n*{{NetT|108,654}}\n*{{DWT|11,132}}\n | Ship depth            =  24\n | Ship decks            = 15\n | Ship deck clearance   = 7\n | Ship ramps            = 4\n | Ship power =6 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46 (6 \u00d7 {{convert|12,600|kW|lk=on|abbr=on}})\n | Ship propulsion =*[[Diesel-electric transmission|Diesel-electric]]\n* 2 \u00d7 [[ABB (company)|ABB]] [[Azipod]]s and 1 \u00d7 [[Fixipod]]\n* 4 \u00d7 [[bow thruster]]s\n | Ship speed            = {{convert|23.7|kn|lk=in}}\n | Ship capacity         = 3,138 passengers\n | Ship crew             = 1,181\n | Ship notes            = <ref name=\"cruise travel guide\">{{cite journal|date=January\u2013February 2009|title=Cruise Ship Guide|journal=Cruise Travel|publisher=Lakeside Publishing Company|pages=37\u201343|issn=0199-5111}}</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Voyager of the Seas''''' is the [[lead ship]] of the {{sclass-|Voyager|cruise ship|4}} of [[cruise ship]]s operated by [[Royal Caribbean International]] (RCI).  Constructed by [[Kv\u00e6rner Masa-Yards]] at its [[Perno shipyard|Turku New Shipyard]] in [[Turku]], Finland, she was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on November 27, 1998, and formally named by Olympic [[figure skating|figure skater]] [[Katarina Witt]] on November 20, 1999.\n\nUpon her departure on her [[maiden voyage]] the following day, November 21, 1999, ''Voyager of the Seas'' was the largest cruise ship in the world, although she was overtaken the following year by her [[sister ship]] {{ship||Explorer of the Seas}}. She measured {{GT|137,276|disp=long}} at launch and following a refit in 2014 her tonnage increased to {{GT|138,194}}.<ref name=dnv/> She is {{convert|311|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|long overall]], has a [[waterline]] [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|36.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}} and a height of {{convert|63|m|ftin|abbr=on}}.\n\n==Design==\n''Voyager of the Seas'' included the first rock climbing wall (mounted on the funnel) and the first ice-skating rink at sea.{{sfn|Saunders|2013|p=94}}\n\nIn October and November 2014, ''Voyager of the Seas'' underwent a refit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asia.etbnews.com/220135/enjoy-first-surfing-experience-sea-asia-voyager-seas/ |title=Enjoy the first surfing experience at sea in Asia on Voyager of the Seas |website=ETB Travel News |access-date=2014-10-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019041023/http://asia.etbnews.com/220135/enjoy-first-surfing-experience-sea-asia-voyager-seas/ |archive-date=19 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The modifications included the installation of an outdoor movie screen near the pool and replacing the [[inline skating]] track with a [[flowrider]] surf simulator.<ref name=voy_flowrider>{{cite web |title=Voyager Class Flowrider Refurbishment|url=http://www.mobimar.com/news-voyager_class_flowrider_refurbishment|work=Mobimar.com|access-date=27 January 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307203825/http://www.mobimar.com/news-voyager_class_flowrider_refurbishment|archive-date=7 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Voyager of the Seas'' underwent a US$97 million refit in September 2019 which included the addition of 72 passenger cabins and water slides.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://cruisefever.net/royal-caribbean-cruise-ship-resumes-cruises-after-97-million-renovation/|title= Royal Caribbean Cruise Ship Resumes Cruises After $97 Million Renovation|first=Ben |last=Souza|date= 23 October 2019|website=cruisefever.net}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Saunders-Giants of the Seas}}\t\n* {{Smith-Cruise Ships-2010}}\t\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Voyager of the Seas}}\n* [http://www.royalcaribbean.com/findacruise/ships/class/ship/home.do?shipClassCode=VY&shipCode=VY&br=R Official website]\n\n{{Largest passenger ships}}\